## purpose
Defines the canonical architectural role of life in CivilizationOS.

## design_intent
Life is the bounded continuity layer
that gives meaningful persistence
to entities, actors, relations, conditions, and transitions
across time.

Life is not identical to a single event or single state.
It is the continuity model that binds
existence,
change,
state progression,
and historical retention.

## architectural_position
Life sits between:
- world containment
- identity continuity
- family/relationship continuity
- medical/education/work continuity
- history accumulation
- event-driven change

## required_behavior
- life continuity must remain explicit
- current and historical life states must remain distinct
- change over time must remain reviewable
- bounded transitions must remain explicit
- invalid continuity assumptions must fail closed

## canonical_rules
- life truth must not be replaced by a single snapshot
- current state must not erase historical state
- life continuity must remain attributable
- state transition without basis is prohibited
- ambiguity in continuity fails closed

## state_model
The life domain distinguishes:
- initialized life state
- active life state
- changed life state
- restricted life state
- historical life state
- closed life state

## actor_boundary
- self-bearing actor
- linked actor
- reviewer
- operator
- adapter

## decision_matrix
- if continuity basis is missing, stop mutation
- if current and historical states are mixed, fail closed
- if transition basis is unclear, route to review
- if state is closed, preserve historical continuity

## review_checklist
- continuity model is explicit
- state model is explicit
- transition basis is explicit
- historical distinction is explicit
